snippet.textDisplay: This talk presumes that neoliberal capitalism is the necessary paradigm.  I reject that.  If we can overcome scarcity of resources through automation, 3-D printing, laboratory production, etc., then money becomes less necessary, since money is just the uneven division of resources made necessary out of that scarcity.  Money is a measurement of greed.  Let's teach that to our children?  I'd sooner teach a consideration of overcoming money as a social problem.

snippet.textDisplay: The real money wasn't what changed their behavior.  It was changing the incentive of the game.  Listen closely to his story.  His kids bent the rules for each other because they play games as a family for fun.  If someone is out of the Monopoly game, they aren't having fun with the family so they did things to keep each other in the game.  Along with the real money, he added stakes to the game by saying the winner gets $20.  THAT is what changed their behavior.  Their incentives changed from just enjoying each other's company and having fun together to wanting to win to get the reward.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yeah we don't use cash today.... because the government and IRS can't track it. They won't stand for that.
When you do try to withdraw more than 300, you'll find that your bank/atm won't allow it unless you go to a real teller (most Chase branches don't have in-person tellers). If you withdraw too much, the bank will notify the IRS of your transaction.
And when you do try to deposit a few thousand, you risk that the IRS will conduct a Civil Forfeiture and empty your account because certainly you must be trying to evade taxes.
So many stores won't even accept cash now, because the IRS presumes the company will evade taxes if they handle in cash. So many small companies have lost their entire accounts due to civil forfeitures.
If a company does take cash, they won't accept $100 bills (usually anything over a 20 bill), so what are you going to buy a Macbook with 125 x $20 bills?
Many toll booths down here in Florida also won't accept cash.
Many utility companies charge you a fee if you try to pay by mail (like with a check). And it's not possible to pay with cash so forget it.
Then, go try to get a loan for a house or car after you've been cash-only your whole life and have no credit.
Then, you've got all these credit cards and online services which offer 1% to 3% cash back when you use their card.
Then, go try to buy something on amazon online, and hand your computer cash. You going to insert cash into the CD Drive?

So what are we supposed to do? Not have electricity and only shop at flea markets?
We don't have a choice anymore.
